# Production Quality Rule: No Demo Code

Build minimal production-grade vertical slices, not fake demos. Prefer smaller complete functionality over broad incomplete scaffolding.

## Definition of done for any feature

A feature is complete only when it includes:

- typed frontend and backend contracts
- persisted state in PostgreSQL, Redis, Meilisearch, or object storage as appropriate
- validation at API boundaries
- meaningful error handling and user-safe error messages
- RBAC/auth checks when user/admin access differs
- audit logs for admin mutations and sensitive operations
- i18n keys for user-facing text
- tests for critical domain logic
- seed/dev data through real schemas, not hard-coded arrays

## Forbidden implementation shortcuts

- Do not use in-memory arrays as the source of truth for domain data.
- Do not create UI-only pages that are not connected to real API contracts.
- Do not fake analytics dashboards with static chart numbers.
- Do not import raw JSON directly into canonical tables. Use staging, profiling, validation, and transform.
- Do not hard-code user-facing copy outside i18n resources.
- Do not implement RBAC only in the frontend. Backend must enforce permissions.
- Do not hide errors with empty catch blocks.
- Do not leave required workflows as TODO placeholders.
- Do not skip Prisma migrations for persistent data.
- Do not use localStorage for data that must survive across devices or be audited.

## Allowed temporary implementations

- Mock providers are allowed only behind explicit provider interfaces.
- External APIs may use local providers in development when keys are unavailable.
- Seed/demo data is allowed only through real schema + clear seed labels.
- A minimal screen is allowed if it performs the real workflow end-to-end.

## When scope is too large

Implement a smaller vertical slice that is real. Do not make broad fake coverage. Example: one real flashcard deck with SRS persistence is better than ten static flashcard screens.
